docs.text:
The 
mapsengine1
 command-line interface 
(CLI)
 allows to use most features of the 
Google Maps Engine
 service from the comfort of your terminal.


By default all output is printed to standard out, but flags can be set to direct it into a file independent of your shell's
capabilities. Errors will be printed to standard error, and cause the program's exit code to be non-zero.


If data-structures are requested, these will be returned as pretty-printed JSON, to be useful as input to other tools.


Everything else about the 
Maps Engine
 API can be found at the

official documentation site
.


Downloads


You can download the pre-compiled 64bit binaries for the following platforms:




 
ubuntu


 
osx




Find the source code 
on github
.

  mapsengine1 --help

Configuration:
  [--scope 
url
]...
            Specify the authentication a method should be executed in. Each scope
            requires the user to grant this application permission to use it.
            If unset, it defaults to the shortest scope url for a particular method.
  --config-dir 
folder

            A directory into which we will store our persistent data. Defaults to
            a user-writable directory that we will create during the first invocation.
            [default: ~/.google-service-cli]
  --debug
            Output all server communication to standard error. `tx` and `rx` are placed
            into the same stream.
  --debug-auth
            Output all communication related to authentication to standard error. `tx`
            and `rx` are placed into the same stream.





Configuration


The program will store all persistent data in the 
~/.google-service-cli
 directory in 
JSON
 files prefixed with 
mapsengine1-
.  You can change the directory used to store configuration with the 
--config-dir
 flag on a per-invocation basis.


More information about the various kinds of persistent data are given in the following paragraphs.


Authentication


Most APIs require a user to authenticate any request. If this is the case, the 
scope
 determines the 
set of permissions granted. The granularity of these is usually no more than 
read-only
 or 
full-access
.


If not set, the system will automatically select the smallest feasible scope, e.g. when invoking a
method that is read-only, it will ask only for a read-only scope. 
You may use the 
--scope
 flag to specify a scope directly. 
All applicable scopes are documented in the respective method's CLI documentation.


The first time a scope is used, the user is asked for permission. Follow the instructions given 
by the CLI to grant permissions, or to decline.


If a scope was authenticated by the user, the respective information will be stored as 
JSON
 in the configuration
directory, e.g. 
~/.google-service-cli/mapsengine1-token-
scope-hash
.json
. No manual management of these tokens
is necessary.


To revoke granted authentication, please refer to the 
official documentation
.


Application Secrets


In order to allow any application to use Google services, it will need to be registered using the 

Google Developer Console
. APIs the application may use are then enabled for it
one by one. Most APIs can be used for free and have a daily quota.


To allow more comfortable usage of the CLI without forcing anyone to register an own application, the CLI
comes with a default application secret that is configured accordingly. This also means that heavy usage
all around the world may deplete the daily quota.


You can workaround this limitation by putting your own secrets file at this location: 

~/.google-service-cli/mapsengine1-secret.json
, assuming that the required 
mapsengine
 API 
was enabled for it. Such a secret file can be downloaded in the 
Google Developer Console
 at 

APIs 
 auth -
 Credentials -
 Download JSON
 and used as is.


Learn more about how to setup Google projects and enable APIs using the 
official documentation
.


Debugging


Even though the CLI does its best to provide usable error messages, sometimes it might be desirable to know
what exactly led to a particular issue. This is done by allowing all client-server communication to be 
output to standard error 
as-is
.


The 
--debug
 flag will print all client-server communication to standard error, whereas the 
--debug-auth
 flag
will cause all communication related to authentication to standard error.
If the 
--debug
 flag is set, error-results will be debug-printed, possibly yielding more information about the 
issue at hand.


You may consider redirecting standard error into a file for ease of use, e.g. 
mapsengine1 --debug 
resource
 
method
 [options] 2
debug.txt
.

docs.text:
Return metadata for a particular asset.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine.readonly




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine.readonly
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 assets get ...


Required Scalar Argument




id
 
(string)


The ID of the asset.








Optional Output Flags


The method's return value a JSON encoded structure, which will be written to standard output by default.




-o out


out
 specifies the 
destination
 to which to write the server's result to.
  It will be a JSON-encoded structure.
  The 
destination
 may be 
-
 to indicate standard output, or a filepath that is to contain the received bytes.
  If unset, it defaults to standard output.








Optional General Properties


The following properties can configure any call, and are not specific to this method.






-p alt=string




Data format for the response.








-p fields=string




Selector specifying which fields to include in a partial response.








-p key=string




API key. Your API key identifies your project and provides you with API access, quota, and reports. Required unless you provide an OAuth 2.0 token.








-p oauth-token=string




OAuth 2.0 token for the current user.








-p pretty-print=boolean




Returns response with indentations and line breaks.








-p quota-user=string




Available to use for quota purposes for server-side applications. Can be any arbitrary string assigned to a user, but should not exceed 40 characters. Overrides userIp if both are provided.








-p user-ip=string




IP address of the site where the request originates. Use this if you want to enforce per-user limits.

docs.text:
Return all assets readable by the current user.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine.readonly




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine.readonly
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 assets list ...


Optional Output Flags


The method's return value a JSON encoded structure, which will be written to standard output by default.




-o out


out
 specifies the 
destination
 to which to write the server's result to.
  It will be a JSON-encoded structure.
  The 
destination
 may be 
-
 to indicate standard output, or a filepath that is to contain the received bytes.
  If unset, it defaults to standard output.








Optional Method Properties


You may set the following properties to further configure the call. Please note that 
-p
 is followed by one 
or more key-value-pairs, and is called like this 
-p k1=v1 k2=v2
 even though the listing below repeats the

-p
 for completeness.






-p modified-after=string




An RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Returned assets will have been modified at or after this time.








-p created-after=string




An RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Returned assets will have been created at or after this time.








-p tags=string




A comma separated list of tags. Returned assets will contain all the tags from the list.








-p search=string




An unstructured search string used to filter the set of results based on asset metadata.








-p project-id=string




The ID of a Maps Engine project, used to filter the response. To list all available projects with their IDs, send a Projects: list request. You can also find your project ID as the value of the DashboardPlace:cid URL parameter when signed in to mapsengine.google.com.








-p max-results=integer




The maximum number of items to include in a single response page. The maximum supported value is 100.








-p page-token=string




The continuation token, used to page through large result sets. To get the next page of results, set this parameter to the value of nextPageToken from the previous response.








-p bbox=string




A bounding box, expressed as 
west,south,east,north
. If set, only assets which intersect this bounding box will be returned.








-p creator-email=string




An email address representing a user. Returned assets that have been created by the user associated with the provided email address.








-p created-before=string




An RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Returned assets will have been created at or before this time.








-p modified-before=string




An RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Returned assets will have been modified at or before this time.








-p role=string




The role parameter indicates that the response should only contain assets where the current user has the specified level of access.








-p type=string




A comma separated list of asset types. Returned assets will have one of the types from the provided list. Supported values are 
map
, 
layer
, 
rasterCollection
 and 
table
.

docs.text:
Create a layer asset.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 layers create ...


Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Layer:
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  datasource-type: string
  description: string
  draft-access-list: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  last-modified-time: string
  last-modifier-email: string
  layer-type: string
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  published-access-list: string
  publishing-status: string
  style:
    feature-info:
      content: string
    type: string
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bbox=0.617752856951


A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this Layer. The box is expressed as \
west, south, east, north\
. The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






creation-time=sit


The creation time of this layer. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=stet


The email address of the creator of this layer. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






datasource-type=sed


Deprecated: The type of the datasources used to build this Layer. Note: This has been replaced by layerType, but is still available for now to maintain backward compatibility.






description=et


The description of this Layer, supplied by the author.






draft-access-list=dolores


Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






etag=kasd


The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.






id=accusam


A globally unique ID, used to refer to this Layer.






last-modified-time=takimata


The last modified time of this layer. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






last-modifier-email=justo


The email address of the last modifier of this layer. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






layer-type=amet.


The type of the datasources used to build this Layer. This should be used instead of datasourceType. At least one of layerType and datasourceType and must be specified, but layerType takes precedence.






name=erat


The name of this Layer, supplied by the author.






processing-status=labore


The processing status of this layer.






project-id=sea


The ID of the project that this Layer is in.






published-access-list=nonumy


Deprecated: The access list to whom view permissions are granted. The value must be the name of a Maps Engine access list of the Map Viewer type, and the user must be a viewer on that list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






publishing-status=dolores


The publishing status of this layer.








style.feature-info    content=gubergren




HTML template of the info window. If not provided, a default template with all attributes will be generated.








..    type=sadipscing




The type of the vector style. Currently, only displayRule is supported.








..    writers-can-edit-permissions=true




If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Delete a layer.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope

Required Scalar Argument




id
 
(string)


The ID of the layer. Only the layer creator or project owner are permitted to delete. If the layer is published, or included in a map, the request will fail. Unpublish the layer, and remove it from all maps prior to deleting.

No description provided.








-p created-after=string




An RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Returned assets will have been created at or after this time.








-p modified-after=string




An RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Returned assets will have been modified at or after this time.








-p project-id=string




The ID of a Maps Engine project, used to filter the response. To list all available projects with their IDs, send a Projects: list request. You can also find your project ID as the value of the DashboardPlace:cid URL parameter when signed in to mapsengine.google.com.








-p search=string




An unstructured search string used to filter the set of results based on asset metadata.








-p tags=string




A comma separated list of tags. Returned assets will contain all the tags from the list.








-p max-results=integer




The maximum number of items to include in a single response page. The maximum supported value is 100.








-p page-token=string




The continuation token, used to page through large result sets. To get the next page of results, set this parameter to the value of nextPageToken from the previous response.








-p bbox=string




A bounding box, expressed as 
west,south,east,north
. If set, only assets which intersect this bounding box will be returned.








-p creator-email=string




An email address representing a user. Returned assets that have been created by the user associated with the provided email address.








-p created-before=string




An RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Returned assets will have been created at or before this time.








-p modified-before=string




An RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Returned assets will have been modified at or before this time.








-p role=string




The role parameter indicates that the response should only contain assets where the current user has the specified level of access.

Mutate a layer asset.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 layers patch ...


Required Scalar Argument




id
 
(string)


The ID of the layer.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Layer:
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  datasource-type: string
  description: string
  draft-access-list: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  last-modified-time: string
  last-modifier-email: string
  layer-type: string
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  published-access-list: string
  publishing-status: string
  style:
    feature-info:
      content: string
    type: string
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bbox=0.348101942899


A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this Layer. The box is expressed as \
west, south, east, north\
. The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






creation-time=no


The creation time of this layer. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=justo


The email address of the creator of this layer. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






datasource-type=justo


Deprecated: The type of the datasources used to build this Layer. Note: This has been replaced by layerType, but is still available for now to maintain backward compatibility.






description=et


The description of this Layer, supplied by the author.






draft-access-list=et


Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






etag=diam


The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.






id=ipsum


A globally unique ID, used to refer to this Layer.






last-modified-time=lorem


The last modified time of this layer. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






last-modifier-email=et


The email address of the last modifier of this layer. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






layer-type=duo


The type of the datasources used to build this Layer. This should be used instead of datasourceType. At least one of layerType and datasourceType and must be specified, but layerType takes precedence.






name=aliquyam


The name of this Layer, supplied by the author.






processing-status=sea


The processing status of this layer.






project-id=lorem


The ID of the project that this Layer is in.






published-access-list=eos


Deprecated: The access list to whom view permissions are granted. The value must be the name of a Maps Engine access list of the Map Viewer type, and the user must be a viewer on that list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






publishing-status=erat


The publishing status of this layer.








style.feature-info    content=sadipscing




HTML template of the info window. If not provided, a default template with all attributes will be generated.








..    type=dolor




The type of the vector style. Currently, only displayRule is supported.








..    writers-can-edit-permissions=true




If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.

You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.

...

Create a map asset.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 maps create ...


Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Map:
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  description: string
  draft-access-list: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  last-modified-time: string
  last-modifier-email: string
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  published-access-list: string
  publishing-status: string
  versions: [string]
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bbox=0.0438804035801


A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this Map. The box is expressed as \
west, south, east, north\
. The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






creation-time=no


The creation time of this map. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=labore


The email address of the creator of this map. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






description=eirmod


The description of this Map, supplied by the author.






draft-access-list=dolore


Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






etag=invidunt


The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.






id=aliquyam


A globally unique ID, used to refer to this Map.






last-modified-time=accusam


The last modified time of this map. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






last-modifier-email=lorem


The email address of the last modifier of this map. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






name=sea


The name of this Map, supplied by the author.






processing-status=et


The processing status of this map. Map processing is automatically started once a map becomes ready for processing.






project-id=duo


The ID of the project that this Map is in.






published-access-list=et


Deprecated: The access list to whom view permissions are granted. The value must be the name of a Maps Engine access list of the Map Viewer type, and the user must be a viewer on that list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






publishing-status=eirmod


The publishing status of this map.






versions=sanctus


Deprecated: An array containing the available versions of this Map. Currently may only contain 
published
. The publishingStatus field should be used instead.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






writers-can-edit-permissions=true


If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Mutate a map asset.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 maps patch ...


Required Scalar Argument




id
 
(string)


The ID of the map.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Map:
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  description: string
  draft-access-list: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  last-modified-time: string
  last-modifier-email: string
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  published-access-list: string
  publishing-status: string
  versions: [string]
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bbox=0.549609244211


A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this Map. The box is expressed as \
west, south, east, north\
. The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






creation-time=et


The creation time of this map. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=consetetur


The email address of the creator of this map. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






description=ut


The description of this Map, supplied by the author.






draft-access-list=ea


Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






etag=sed


The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.






id=dolor


A globally unique ID, used to refer to this Map.






last-modified-time=dolor


The last modified time of this map. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






last-modifier-email=dolor


The email address of the last modifier of this map. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






name=et


The name of this Map, supplied by the author.






processing-status=consetetur


The processing status of this map. Map processing is automatically started once a map becomes ready for processing.






project-id=amet.


The ID of the project that this Map is in.






published-access-list=voluptua.


Deprecated: The access list to whom view permissions are granted. The value must be the name of a Maps Engine access list of the Map Viewer type, and the user must be a viewer on that list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






publishing-status=lorem


The publishing status of this map.






versions=gubergren


Deprecated: An array containing the available versions of this Map. Currently may only contain 
published
. The publishingStatus field should be used instead.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






writers-can-edit-permissions=true


If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Create a raster collection asset.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 raster-collections create ...


Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


RasterCollection:
  attribution: string
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  description: string
  draft-access-list: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  last-modified-time: string
  last-modifier-email: string
  mosaic: boolean
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  raster-type: string
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    attribution=consetetur


The name of the attribution to be used for this RasterCollection. Note: Attribution is returned in response to a get request but not a list request. After requesting a list of raster collections, you
ll need to send a get request to retrieve the attribution for each raster collection.






bbox=0.568975580071


A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this RasterCollection. The box is expressed as \
west, south, east, north\
. The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






creation-time=vero


The creation time of this RasterCollection. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=sadipscing


The email address of the creator of this raster collection. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






description=invidunt


The description of this RasterCollection, supplied by the author.






draft-access-list=consetetur


Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






etag=dolore


The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.






id=duo


A globally unique ID, used to refer to this RasterCollection.






last-modified-time=aliquyam


The last modified time of this RasterCollection. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






last-modifier-email=lorem


The email address of the last modifier of this raster collection. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






mosaic=true


True if this RasterCollection is a mosaic.






name=clita


The name of this RasterCollection, supplied by the author.






processing-status=consetetur


The processing status of this RasterCollection.






project-id=takimata


The ID of the project that this RasterCollection is in.






raster-type=nonumy


The type of rasters contained within this RasterCollection.






writers-can-edit-permissions=true


If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Mutate a raster collection asset.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 raster-collections patch ...


Required Scalar Argument




id
 
(string)


The ID of the raster collection.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


RasterCollection:
  attribution: string
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  description: string
  draft-access-list: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  last-modified-time: string
  last-modifier-email: string
  mosaic: boolean
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  raster-type: string
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    attribution=sanctus


The name of the attribution to be used for this RasterCollection. Note: Attribution is returned in response to a get request but not a list request. After requesting a list of raster collections, you
ll need to send a get request to retrieve the attribution for each raster collection.






bbox=0.429944554623


A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this RasterCollection. The box is expressed as \
west, south, east, north\
. The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






creation-time=at


The creation time of this RasterCollection. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=labore


The email address of the creator of this raster collection. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






description=invidunt


The description of this RasterCollection, supplied by the author.






draft-access-list=ea


Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






etag=sadipscing


The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.






id=rebum.


A globally unique ID, used to refer to this RasterCollection.






last-modified-time=dolore


The last modified time of this RasterCollection. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






last-modifier-email=nonumy


The email address of the last modifier of this raster collection. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






mosaic=true


True if this RasterCollection is a mosaic.






name=aliquyam


The name of this RasterCollection, supplied by the author.






processing-status=sit


The processing status of this RasterCollection.






project-id=eirmod


The ID of the project that this RasterCollection is in.






raster-type=consetetur


The type of rasters contained within this RasterCollection.






writers-can-edit-permissions=false


If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.  For example, a structure like this:  RasterCollectionsRastersBatchInsertRequest:
  ids: [string]  can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.   -r .    ids=gubergren  An array of Raster asset IDs to be added to this RasterCollection.  Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.     About Cursors  The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:   The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the  .  character. Fields can be nested such as in  -r f.s.o  .  The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with  . , e.g.  -r .s.s  You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify  -r struct.sub_struct=bar .  You can move the cursor one level up by using  .. . Each additional  .  moves it up one additional level. E.g.  ...  would go three levels up.

can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.

mask-type=amet


The mask processing type of this Raster.






name=accusam


The name of this Raster, supplied by the author.






processing-status=clita

project-id=diam

docs.text:
Create a skeleton raster asset for upload.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 rasters upload ...


Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Raster:
  acquisition-time:
    end: string
    precision: string
    start: string
  attribution: string
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  description: string
  draft-access-list: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  last-modified-time: string
  last-modifier-email: string
  mask-type: string
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  raster-type: string
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .acquisition-time    end=invidunt


The end time if acquisition time is a range. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






precision=ut


The precision of acquisition time.








start=dolores




The acquisition time, or start time if acquisition time is a range. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).








..    attribution=eos




The name of the attribution to be used for this Raster.






bbox=0.236711616706


A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this Raster. The box is expressed as \
west, south, east, north\
. The numbers represent latitudes and longitudes in decimal degrees.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






creation-time=duo


The creation time of this raster. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=sed


The email address of the creator of this raster. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






description=aliquyam


The description of this Raster, supplied by the author.






draft-access-list=ea


Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






etag=ea


The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.






id=et


A globally unique ID, used to refer to this Raster.






last-modified-time=dolor


The last modified time of this raster. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






last-modifier-email=diam


The email address of the last modifier of this raster. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






mask-type=kasd


The mask processing type of this Raster.






name=invidunt


The name of this Raster, supplied by the author.






processing-status=rebum.


The processing status of this Raster.






project-id=lorem


The ID of the project that this Raster is in.






raster-type=clita


The type of this Raster. Always 
image
 today.






writers-can-edit-permissions=true


If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Scopes

.

scope

The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.

. The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.

creation-time=at


The creation time of this table. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=consetetur

description=et

last-modifier-email=nonumy


The email address of the last modifier of this table. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






name=rebum.


The name of this table, supplied by the author.






processing-status=lorem


The processing status of this table.






project-id=lorem


The ID of the project to which the table belongs.






published-access-list=diam


Deprecated: The access list to whom view permissions are granted. The value must be the name of a Maps Engine access list of the Map Viewer type, and the user must be a viewer on that list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






schema    primary-geometry=ut


The name of the column that contains a feature
s geometry. This field can be omitted during table create; Google Maps Engine supports only a single geometry column, which must be named geometry and be the first object in the columns array.








primary-key=ut




The name of the column that contains the unique identifier of a Feature.








..    source-encoding=amet.




Encoding of the uploaded files. Valid values include UTF-8, CP1251, ISO 8859-1, and Shift_JIS.






writers-can-edit-permissions=false


If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.

Update the supplied features.


A single batchPatch request can update:




Up to 50 features.


A combined total of 10 000 vertices.
Feature limits are documented in the Supported data formats and limits article of the Google Maps Engine help center. Note that free and paid accounts have different limits.




Feature updates use HTTP PATCH semantics:




A supplied value replaces an existing value (if any) in that field.


Omitted fields remain unchanged.


Complex values in geometries and properties must be replaced as atomic units. For example, providing just the coordinates of a geometry is not allowed; the complete geometry, including type, must be supplied.


Setting a property
s value to null deletes that property.
For more information about updating features, read Updating features in the Google Maps Engine developer

.

mapsengine1 --scope 
scope

Required Scalar Arguments




id
 
(string)

filename

resumable

docs.text:
Mutate a table asset.


Scopes


You will need authorization for the 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
 scope to make a valid call.


If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/mapsengine
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
mapsengine1 --scope 
scope
 tables patch ...


Required Scalar Argument




id
 
(string)


The ID of the table.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Table:
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  description: string
  draft-access-list: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  last-modified-time: string
  last-modifier-email: string
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  published-access-list: string
  schema:
    primary-geometry: string
    primary-key: string
  source-encoding: string
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bbox=0.615268420345


A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this Table. The box is expressed as \
west, south, east, north\
. The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.


Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.






creation-time=sanctus


The creation time of this table. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






creator-email=voluptua.


The email address of the creator of this table. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






description=dolor


The description of this table, supplied by the author.






draft-access-list=et


Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






etag=et


The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.






id=vero


A globally unique ID, used to refer to this table.






last-modified-time=ut


The last modified time of this table. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).






last-modifier-email=sed


The email address of the last modifier of this table. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.






name=et


The name of this table, supplied by the author.






processing-status=ipsum


The processing status of this table.






project-id=justo


The ID of the project to which the table belongs.






published-access-list=dolore


Deprecated: The access list to whom view permissions are granted. The value must be the name of a Maps Engine access list of the Map Viewer type, and the user must be a viewer on that list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.






schema    primary-geometry=vero


The name of the column that contains a feature
s geometry. This field can be omitted during table create; Google Maps Engine supports only a single geometry column, which must be named geometry and be the first object in the columns array.








primary-key=dolor




The name of the column that contains the unique identifier of a Feature.








..    source-encoding=takimata




Encoding of the uploaded files. Valid values include UTF-8, CP1251, ISO 8859-1, and Shift_JIS.






writers-can-edit-permissions=true


If true, WRITERs of the asset are able to edit the asset permissions.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.  For example, a structure like this:  Table:
  bbox: [number]
  creation-time: string
  creator-email: string
  description: string

  id: string

  last-modifier-email: string
  name: string
  processing-status: string
  project-id: string
  published-access-list: string
  schema:
    primary-geometry: string
    primary-key: string
  source-encoding: string
  writers-can-edit-permissions: boolean  can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.   -r .    bbox=0.169900298723  A rectangular bounding box which contains all of the data in this Table. The box is expressed as \ west, south, east, north\ . The numbers represent latitude and longitude in decimal degrees.  Each invocation of this argument appends the given value to the array.    creation-time=sed  The creation time of this table. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).    creator-email=no  The email address of the creator of this table. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.    description=invidunt  The description of this table, supplied by the author.    draft-access-list=rebum.  Deprecated: The name of an access list of the Map Editor type. The user on whose behalf the request is being sent must be an editor on that access list. Note: Google Maps Engine no longer uses access lists. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.    etag=labore  The ETag, used to refer to the current version of the asset.    id=aliquyam  A globally unique ID, used to refer to this table.    last-modified-time=elitr  The last modified time of this table. The value is an RFC 3339 formatted date-time value (e.g. 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).    last-modifier-email=consetetur  The email address of the last modifier of this table. This is only returned on GET requests and not LIST requests.    name=sea  The name of this table, supplied by the author.    processing-status=elitr  The processing status of this table.    project-id=at  The ID of the project to which the table belongs.    published-access-list=sea  Deprecated: The access list to whom view permissions are granted. Instead, each asset has its own list of permissions. For backward compatibility, the API still accepts access lists for projects that are already using access lists. If you created a GME account/project after July 14th, 2014, you will not be able to send API requests that include access lists. Note: This is an input field only. It is not returned in response to a list or get request.    schema    primary-geometry=consetetur  The name of the column that contains a feature s geometry. This field can be omitted during table create; Google Maps Engine supports only a single geometry column, which must be named geometry and be the first object in the columns array.     primary-key=diam   The name of the column that contains the unique identifier of a Feature.     ..    source-encoding=accusam   Encoding of the uploaded files.
